</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utheodwynriddermark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TheodwynRiddermark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 332<br> <font color=#E9D756>(8/18/02 2:49:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3559.topic&index=23>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Off Topic Racist Rant...</span><hr size=1> I don't generally do this.<br>
<br>
But this one gets my goat.<br>
<br>
This is the United States of America.  The de facto language is English.  If you live here, you should learn it.<br>
<br>
Period.<br>
<br>
Learning languages is good for you, blah blah blah.  Being culturally aware is good for you, blah blah blah.<br>
<br>
Pull your @#%$ heads out.<br>
<br>
I'm one hundred percent Filipino.  I'm a first generation American.  My parents struggled through naturalization, swore citizenship here.  They followed every rule.  My grandfathers shed blood for the cause of democracy, championed by the United States.  My maternal grandfather was a Master Sergeant and Quartermaster of the U.S. Army and served in World War II.  My paternal grandfather was an officer of the Philippine military, and was similarly decorated by the U.S.<br>
<br>
I speak Spanish, French, Tagalog, and English fluently.  I can get by daily phrases in Japanese, can navigate with basic amounts of German, Italian, and Portuguese, and can say &quot;thank you&quot; and &quot;how are you&quot; in Mandarin and Cantonese.  I have studied enough Latin to know and understand the roots of romance languages.  I am familiar with better than average amounts of world history.  I know that the origin of Aryan is India, go figure.  I studied the schism of the original three sects of Islam.  I know how Hindi and several related dialects sprung from Sanskrit.  I can very often with decent accuracy determine to within 300 miles of your surname's origin, anywhere in the world.  I can tell from your name if you are from North India or South India.  I know at a glance if you are Punjabi or Sikh.  I speak dialects, I can do accents.  I can sing the entire Soviet anthem, and translate it.  I live in California.<br>
<br>
And this is still the @#%$ United States of America.   The Constitution is written in English.  Wanna know your rights?  Better @#%$ learn it.<br>
<br>
My tax dollars are squandered in printing the California Driver's Manual in more languages than I can shake a stick at.  And the street signs are still printed in Latin/Roman/Romanji/whatever-your-language's-word-for-it-is.  Idiocy.<br>
<br>
They want to print ballots in Tagalog.  Dumbfucks.  Spend 3 million dollars of taxpayer money in a flagging economy to print ballots in Tagalog.  Duh.  Guess what?  Philippine government documents are in English.  Can one possibly be more stupid?<br>
<br>
Tolerance expressed in the way many of you suggest is why my tax dollars pay for ESL programs that people don't even attend regularly!  Heck, go read <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.vdare.com/guzzardi/joe_education.htm.">www.vdare.com/guzzardi/jo...ation.htm.</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Japanese street signs are increasingly converting to Romanji.  And we print the drivers manual in kanji and katakana?  Ass backwards.<br>
<br>
I love cultural diversity.<br>
<br>
But we are the UNITED States of America.  What unites people?  Common ground.  Common customs.  Common concerns.  Common desires.<br>
<br>
Mexican-American, Filipino-American, Japanese-American.  Hey, are you noticing a pattern here?  What do all these ethnic groups have in common?<br>
<br>
How the @#%$ do you expect to create harmony of unity and diversity at the same time when you justify preserving customs that separate people?  I'm not talking about family values, the right to wear your traditional clothing, sing your traditional songs, or raise your children to be multi-lingual.  By all means, please do, it enriches everyone to maintain diversity.  But to create a society where people can't communicate at a common level?  Where social classes and castes are separated by language?  What next?  Is each ethnic group going to have a different set of laws too?  You know, in the Philippines, corporal punishment is not only accepted, it's normal.  So does that mean Filipino-American children can be whacked with broom handles in the private home of a Filipino-American household, their private property being their own sovereign domain?<br>
<br>
Draw a line somewhere.  Have some balls, take a stand.<br>
<br>
In the Philippines, I speak Tagalog.  In France I speak French.  In Argentina I speak Spanish.  And in the United States of America, I speak English.<br>
<br>
English, American, pick a nit on that point and I encourage you not to breed.  Last thing we need is progeny that can't @#%$ due to sphincter constriction bred through generations.<br>
<br>
I say &quot;thank you&quot; at the Chinese restaurant in whatever dialect that they speak.  It's nice.  It brings people together.  It makes them smile.  It shows my respect for their culture.  The same in any home or business that preserves and shares their culture.<br>
<br>
But this is a country.  It is governed.  It is defended.  It is theoretically united.  Be @#%$ practical.<br>
<br>
Open-minded is good.  Naive and stupid is another.  Several of you are flirting with the not-so-fine-line between the two.<br>
<br>
Go outside, see the day workers lined on the street, unable to gain better employment because we don't encourage them to attain skills (like competent English) that allow them to get better work and improve the lot of themselves and their families.  Watch them band together and drink, wallowing their sorrows, preserving their mistrust of &quot;outsiders&quot;, unwilling to integrate, and all the while feeding their entire family squeezed into one bedroom of a two-bedroom low-income housing unit on food stamps.  Watch their children grow disadvantated, yes right here in the heart of the U.S.A. and join gangs, watch them mark territory, watch them steal, watch their names in the &quot;crime watch&quot; section of your local newspaper.<br>
<br>
What the @#%$ are you thinking?<br>
<br>
Have you so little perception of what divides people and what brings them together?  That the subtle things in common create brotherhood?  That communication is the building block of unity, and that language is an important key of communication?  We're not talking about freedom of expression, we're not talking about preservation of cultural roots, we're talking about different people living in harmony.  And you wonder why Americans are so full of angst.<br>
<br>
Wake the @#%$ up.  You are espousing tolerance of language-racism.  It's not to be tolerated.<br>
<br>
Yes, learn more languages.  Learn more cultures.  Learn more history.  Reach out to your fellow man, take his hand, bid him greeting in his own language, watch his face brighten and return your greeting.  And then wonder why everyone doesn't enjoy that little bright gift of human understanding between strangers.  It's because not everyone is multi-lingual.  Not everyone is multi-cultural.  If you want to create harmony, you've got two choices.  Force everyone to be fantastically multi-lingual.  Or enforce a common tongue.<br>
<br>
Or you can refill your bowl and toke some more.  Your call.<br>
<br>
Theo<br>
