<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  If they want to stop being treated as second class citizens, perhaps they should stop giving the impression of BEING second class citizens.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Let me tell you something. If the majority of folk were prepared to take them at face value rather than automatically class them as third world peasants, then maybe they'd find human beings just like them.<br>
<br>
But most of them aren't given that chance.<br>
<br>
As a migrant myself (albeit an English-speaking one) I've encountered mostly cliches and stereotypes of what I should be when dealing with people. <br>
<br>
The willingness of people to pigeonhole and summarize others based on a very skewed perspective of their homeland isn't unique to the US.<br>
<br>
Ask any Eastern Euorpean migrant to Australia what a &quot;wog&quot; is sometime.<br>
<br>
The Mexicans probably feel that it's a wasted effort to learn English and integrate, simply as the perception that they're worthless cleaners/sweepers/lawn-mowers/burger-flippers/insert-your-racial-cliche here is so endemic. Few people seem willing to accept them as just another bunch of people.<br>
<br>
So they find comfort among their own kind.<br>
<br>
And that's not unique to the US either.<br>
<br>
But, unlike a lot of places that have a rich and polyglot nation, America seems to have gone down the &quot;salad bowl&quot; path, i.e cultures and ethnicities dwell side-by-side but rarely commingle or intermarry. There's a lot of insularity and parochialism fighting against it.<br>
<br>
Slowly but surely, this is being eroded.<br>
<br>
America is actually a pretty fair place, nonetheless. It doesn't impose linguistic or naming restrictions like some nations do, namely Iceland. Folk are free to read, speak and write their own language. America doesn't deny the existence of minorities unlike the nation of my ancestors; Greece.<br>
<br>
So, there's two reasons that don't motivate Mexicans or other NESB foreigners to learn English. One, is the perception people have of them and their nation of origin and two, there is no legal demand on them to adopt the language.<br>
<br>
