<br>
Taken from the United States naturalization and eligibility homepage. It would seem the the US does in fact have a national language, and to become an American citizen you must atleast meet this requirement.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Language <br>
<br>
Applicants for naturalization must be able to read, write, speak, and understand words in ordinary usage in the English language. Applicants exempt from this requirement are those who on the date of filing: <br>
<br>
have been residing in the United States subsequent to a lawful admission for permanent residence for periods totaling 15 years or more and are over 55 years of age; <br>
have been residing in the United States subsequent to a lawful admission for permanent residence for periods totaling 20 years or more and are over 50 years of age; or <br>
have a medically determinable physical or mental impairment, where the impairment affects the applicants ability to learn English. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't face this issue on a daily basis, so it doesn't affect me personally but I do agree that people living in a country should atleast make an effort to know the bare minimum of the native language to function within the society. <p><table align=center>

